(CNN) -- After months of speculation and hype, the first biopic about Apple co-founder Steve Jobs hit theaters Friday. "Jobs," directed by Joshua Michael Stern and starring Ashton Kutcher as the iconic tech guru, spans much of Jobs' early career, from his hippie days at Reed College in 1974 to the launch of the original iPod in 2001. And guess what? Although it omits or glosses over many chapters of Jobs' life, it's not bad. This is the first dramatic feature film to focus solely on the longtime Apple CEO, who died in 2011. A second Steve Jobs movie, written by Aaron Sorkin and adapted from the best-selling Jobs biography by Walter Isaacson, is due as early as next year.
